subject: Remove is_public from reserved attribute in v2

values.-1: This patch needs further work before it can be merged
values.+1: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

messages.message: Uploaded patch set 1.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Uhm, this breaks API stability. You can' just remove a parameter like this. Please see:

https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/APIChangeGuidelines#Generally_Not_Acceptable

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2

FWIW, this doesn't remove the property from the API, it removes it from the ones that are reserved, which means it now *allows* that property to be used by users. If anything, it opens the API a bit more, which in this particular case doesn't seem like a breaking change.

In addition, we've bumped the API version in this cycle too, so this won't break previous API versions.

I'm ok with this change.

Patch Set 1: -Code-Review

Ah, ok sorry I misread that. I'm still not sure changing the usage around that param like this is a backwards compatible change either, but if it's around a version boundary I guess it's ok.

@Ian: because logically it's not a reserved parameter and its removing from the list makes the code cleaner.

Patch Set 1:

What is the behaviour if you are running both v1 and v2?

If I use v2 to mark an image with is_public True, does that change the behaviour when accessing that image via v1?

Patch Set 1:

> If I use v2 to mark an image with is_public True, does that change the behaviour when accessing that image via v1?

To answer my own question ... no. (It correctly gets interpreted as a generic property.)

Patch Set 1:

Yes, is_public in terms of visibility is ignored in v2 and considered as a generic property, so there is no reason to keep it in reserved attributes list, as Fei has mentioned.

Patch Set 1:

Mike, I understand it isn't used in v2. What I'm trying to weigh here is the benefit of allowing this as a generic property versus the confusion it will cause for users familiar with v1 but not v2. I don't know, but I would hazard a guess that this was reserved to prevent confusion when updating usage from v1 to v2. Right now, code setting is_public to affect the visibility of the image in v1 will trigger a 403 error. Users will have to check the documentation and will see that the name they're looking for is visibility. With this merged, users will not see any error and will be baffled as to why their images are not being made public (or private, whichever the case may be).

Patch Set 1:

I do see where Ian is coming from. 

a v2 image show will display the 'generic/uninterpreted property' (allowed with this patch) inline:

 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | Property         | Value                                |
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+
 .
 .
 .
 | is_public        | True                                 |
 .
 .
 .
 +------------------+--------------------------------------+

in the exact same way as v1 will show the 'real/interpreted' 'is_public' field:
 
 +----------------------+--------------------------------------+
 | Property             | Value                                |
 +----------------------+--------------------------------------+
 .
 .
 .
 | is_public            | False                                |
 .
 .
 .
 +----------------------+--------------------------------------+

I wonder if the potential for user confusion outweighs the 'cleaner code' benefit?

Patch Set 1:

Yep, I see it too.But afaik, v1 is going to be deprecated in kilo and after this commit v1->v2 compatibility is ok (if image was created with v1 than all its properties would be exactly the same in v2).
And if someone will create images using v2, and then watch them using deprecated v1 of course it can lead to some incompatibility (very rare btw).
If it is very scary to merge it right now, let's postpone the patch to the point where v1 is completely removed from glance in the L cycle.

Patch Set 1: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

I do agree, other way this would have been problem (restricting usage of previously available attribute), but cleaning up restrictions for something that has no justification is good thing. Thanks Fei.
